.SH "NAME"
Net::Server::Proto::SSL \- Net::Server SSL protocol (deprecated \- use Net::Server::Proto::SSLEAY instead).
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
This module is mostly deprecated \- you will want to look at Net::Server::Proto::SSLEAY instead.
.PP
See Net::Server::Proto.
See Net::Server::Proto::SSLEAY.
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
This original \s-1SSL\s0 module was experimental.  It has been superceeded by
Net::Server::Proto::SSLEAY If anybody has any successes or ideas for
improvment under \s-1SSL\s0, please email <paul@seamons.com>.
.PP
Protocol module for Net::Server.  This module implements a
secure socket layer over tcp (also known as \s-1SSL\s0).
See Net::Server::Proto.
.PP
There is a limit inherent from using IO::Socket::SSL,
namely that only one \s-1SSL\s0 connection can be maintained by
Net::Server.  However, Net::Server should also be able to
maintain any number of \s-1TCP\s0, \s-1UDP\s0, or \s-1UNIX\s0 connections in
addition to the one \s-1SSL\s0 connection.
.PP
Additionally, getline support is very limited and writing directly to
\&\s-1STDOUT\s0 will not work.  This is entirely dependent upon the
implementation of IO::Socket::SSL.  getline may work but the client is
not copied to \s-1STDOUT\s0 under \s-1SSL\s0.  It is suggested that clients sysread
and syswrite to the client handle (located in
\&\f(CW$self\fR\->{server}\->{client} or passed to the process_request subroutine
as the first argument).
.SH "PARAMETERS"
.IX Header "PARAMETERS"
In addition to the normal Net::Server parameters, any of the
\&\s-1SSL\s0 parameters from IO::Socket::SSL may also be specified.
See IO::Socket::SSL for information on setting this up.
.SH "BUGS"
.IX Header "BUGS"
Christopher A Bongaarts pointed out that if the \s-1SSL\s0 negotiation is
slow then the server won't be accepting for that period of time
(because the locking of accept is around both the socket accept and
the \s-1SSL\s0 negotiation).  This means that as it stands now the \s-1SSL\s0
implementation is susceptible to \s-1DOS\s0 attacks.  To fix this will
require deviding up the accept call a little bit more finely which may
not yet be possible with IO::Socket::SSL.  Any ideas or patches on
this bug are welcome.
